<paragraph blockId="16.[811,1455,1938,2027]" box="[813,957,1938,1964]" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[811,1455,1938,2027]" lastBlockId="19.[131,777,215,2028]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="700" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">
In Angeac-Charente, helochelydrids are mostly represented by incomplete isolated shell elements covered by typical tubercles, pustules and crests (
<figureCitation box="[476,608,215,242]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="18.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-29@18.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIG. 12. — Helochelydrid and thalassochelydian turtle remains from Angeac-Charente: A, peripheral plate of Helochelydridae indet. in dorsal view;B, pleural plate of Helochelydridae indet. in dorsal view; C, D, right hyoplastron of Hylaeochelys belli? (Mantell, 1844) (ANG18-5915) in ventral (C) and dorsal (D) views; E, left humerus of Hylaeochelys? belli? (ANG18-5937) in ventral view; F, right humerus (ANG18-5938) in dorsal view;; G, H, Peripheral of Hylaeochelys? belli? (ANG 18-5993) in dorsal (G) and ventral (H) views. Scale bar: A, 1 cm; E-H, 2 cm; B, 3 cm; C, D, 4 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902061/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Fig. 12A, B</figureCitation>
) that diagnose this clade (
<bibRefCitation author="LAPPARENT DE BROIN F. DE &amp; MURELAGA X." box="[260,699,247,274]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="135 - 211" refId="ref42274" refString="LAPPARENT DE BROIN F. DE &amp; MURELAGA X. 1999. - Turtles from the Upper Cretaceous of Lano (Iberian Peninsula). Estudios del Museo de Ciencias Naturales de Alava 14: 135 - 211." type="journal article" year="1999">Lapparent de Broin &amp; Murelaga 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G." pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="65 - 113" refId="ref41684" refString="JOYCE W. G. 2017. - A Review of the Fossil Record of Basal Mesozoic Turtles. Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History 58: 65 - 113. https: // doi. org / 10.3374 / 014.058.0105" type="journal article" year="2017">Joyce 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Probably based on the previous stratigraphical claim by 
<bibRefCitation author="NERAUDEAU D. &amp; ALLAIN R. &amp; BALLEVRE M. &amp; BATTEN D. J. &amp; TAUT E. &amp; COLIN J. P. &amp; DABARD M. P. &amp; GOMEZ V. &amp; EL ALBANI A. &amp; GOMEZ B. &amp; GROSHENY D. &amp; LE LoeUFF J. &amp; LEPRINCE A. &amp; CLOSAS C. &amp; MASURE E. &amp; MAZIN J. - M. &amp; PHILIPPE M. &amp; POUECH J. &amp; TONG H. &amp; TOURNEPICHE J. - F. &amp; VULLO R." box="[242,515,311,337]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref44595" refString="NERAUDEAU D., ALLAIN R., BALLEVRE M., BATTEN D. J., BUFFE- TAUT E., COLIN J. P., DABARD M. P., DAVIERO- GOMEZ V., EL ALBANI A., GOMEZ B., GROSHENY D., LE LoeUFF J., LEPRINCE A., MARTIN- CLOSAS C., MASURE E., MAZIN J. - M., PHILIPPE M., POUECH J., TONG H., TOURNEPICHE J. - F. &amp; VULLO R. 2012. - The Hauterivian-Barremian lignitic bone bed of Angeac (Charente, SW France): stratigraphical, palaeobiological and palaeogeographical implications. Cretaceous Research 37: 1 - 14. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2012.01.006" type="journal article" year="2012">
Néraudeau 
<emphasis box="[373,429,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
that Angeac-Charente was Hauterivian-Barremian in age, 
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G." box="[548,696,343,369]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="65 - 113" refId="ref41684" refString="JOYCE W. G. 2017. - A Review of the Fossil Record of Basal Mesozoic Turtles. Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History 58: 65 - 113. https: // doi. org / 10.3374 / 014.058.0105" type="journal article" year="2017">Joyce (2017)</bibRefCitation>
provisionally referred this material to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lapparent de Broin &amp; Murelaga" authorityYear="1999" box="[516,745,375,401]" class="Reptilia" family="Solemydidae" genus="Helochelydra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nopcsai">
<emphasis box="[516,745,375,401]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Helochelydra nopcsai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species otherwise diagnosed by a shell surface ornamentation consisting of distinct, easily dislocated tubercles. Our observations reveal, however, that the helochelydrid material from Angeac-Charente usually displays distinct tubercles that do not easily dislocate. This ornamentation is more similar to the morphotypes of “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nopcsa" authorityYear="1928" box="[490,628,566,592]" class="Reptilia" family="Solemydidae" genus="Helochelydra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[490,628,566,592]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Helochelydra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” 
<emphasis box="[648,725,566,592]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">anglica</emphasis>
and “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nopcsa" authorityYear="1928" box="[144,283,598,624]" class="Reptilia" family="Solemydidae" genus="Helochelydra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[144,283,598,624]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Helochelydra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” 
<emphasis box="[305,407,598,624]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">bakewelli</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G." box="[427,553,598,624]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="65 - 113" refId="ref41684" refString="JOYCE W. G. 2017. - A Review of the Fossil Record of Basal Mesozoic Turtles. Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History 58: 65 - 113. https: // doi. org / 10.3374 / 014.058.0105" type="journal article" year="2017">Joyce 2017</bibRefCitation>
), respectively from the Purbeck Group (Berriasian) of 
<collectingRegion box="[533,609,630,656]" country="United Kingdom" name="Dorset" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Dorset</collectingRegion>
and the Wealden (Valanginian) of Sussex, 
<collectingCountry box="[452,642,662,688]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">United Kingdom</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D. &amp; MOODY R. T. J. &amp; WALKER C. A." pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="75 - 97" refId="ref41777" refString="JOYCE W. G., CHAPMAN S. D., MOODY R. T. J. &amp; WALKER C. A. 2011. - The skull of the solemydid turtle Helochelydra nopcsai from the Early Cretaceous of the Isle of Wight (UK) and a review of Solemydidae. Special Papers in Palaeontology 86: 75 - 97." type="journal article" year="2011">
Joyce 
<emphasis box="[723,775,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
). That being said, the systematics of Early Cretaceous helochelydrids remains highly confused. For that reason, the helochelydrid material from Angeac-Charente is herein conservatively referred to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nopcsa" authorityYear="1928" box="[421,605,789,815]" family="Helochelydridae" pageId="19" pageNumber="697" rank="family">Helochelydridae</taxonomicName>
indet.
</paragraph>
