<paragraph blockId="19.[131,777,215,2028]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">
The posterior part of a large carapace collected in 2018 and 2020 provides new information on the morphology of the helochelydrid from Angeac-Charente. However, the material is not fully prepared yet and will be described in more detail elsewhere. A raised midline keel on the posterior neurals is clearly observable, which is a character shared with other helochelydrids (
<bibRefCitation author="LYDEKKER R." box="[440,610,1012,1039]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" refId="ref42720" refString="LYDEKKER R. 1889. - Catalogue of the Fossil Reptilia and Amphibia in the British Museum (Natural History). Part III, The Order Chelonia. Trustees of the British Museum, London, 239 p." type="book" year="1889">Lydekker 1889</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="LAPPARENT DE BROIN F. DE &amp; MURELAGA X." pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="135 - 211" refId="ref42274" refString="LAPPARENT DE BROIN F. DE &amp; MURELAGA X. 1999. - Turtles from the Upper Cretaceous of Lano (Iberian Peninsula). Estudios del Museo de Ciencias Naturales de Alava 14: 135 - 211." type="journal article" year="1999">Lapparent de Broin &amp; Murelaga 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="MILNER A. R." box="[421,564,1044,1070]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="1441 - 1467" refId="ref44294" refString="MILNER A. R. 2004. - The turtles of the Purbeck Limestone Group of Dorset, southern England. Palaeontology 47 (6): 1441 - 1467. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 0031 - 0239.2004.00418. x" type="journal article" year="2004">Milner 2004</bibRefCitation>
; Vullo 
<emphasis box="[648,702,1044,1070]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2010; 
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G. &amp; STERLI J. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D." box="[132,324,1076,1103]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="1257 - 1287" refId="ref41904" refString="JOYCE W. G., STERLI J. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D. 2014. - The skeletal morphology of the solemydid turtle Naomichelys speciosa from the Early Cretaceous of Texas. Journal of Paleontology 88 (6): 1257 - 1287. https: // doi. org / 10.1666 / 14 - 002" type="journal article" year="2014">
Joyce 
<emphasis box="[201,256,1076,1102]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G." box="[341,467,1076,1103]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="65 - 113" refId="ref41684" refString="JOYCE W. G. 2017. - A Review of the Fossil Record of Basal Mesozoic Turtles. Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History 58: 65 - 113. https: // doi. org / 10.3374 / 014.058.0105" type="journal article" year="2017">Joyce 2017</bibRefCitation>
; Pérez-García 
<emphasis box="[635,691,1076,1102]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2020). The general morphology resembles that of other species in which this region is sufficiently known, such as “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nopcsa" authorityYear="1928" class="Reptilia" family="Solemydidae" genus="Helochelydra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Helochelydra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” 
<emphasis box="[205,282,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">anglica</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hay" authorityYear="1908" box="[296,518,1172,1198]" class="Reptilia" family="Pleurosternidae" genus="Naomichelys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="speciosa">
<emphasis box="[296,518,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Naomichelys speciosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pérez-García, Espílez, Mampel &amp; Alcalá" authorityYear="2020" box="[533,767,1172,1198]" class="Reptilia" genus="Aragochersis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lignitesta">
<emphasis box="[533,767,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Aragochersis lignitesta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lapparent de Broin &amp; Murelaga" authorityYear="1996" box="[185,410,1204,1230]" class="Reptilia" family="Solemydidae" genus="Solemys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vermiculata">
<emphasis box="[185,410,1204,1230]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Solemys vermiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="LYDEKKER R." box="[430,604,1204,1230]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" refId="ref42720" refString="LYDEKKER R. 1889. - Catalogue of the Fossil Reptilia and Amphibia in the British Museum (Natural History). Part III, The Order Chelonia. Trustees of the British Museum, London, 239 p." type="book" year="1889">Lydekker 1889</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="LAPPARENT DE BROIN F. DE &amp; MURELAGA X." pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="135 - 211" refId="ref42274" refString="LAPPARENT DE BROIN F. DE &amp; MURELAGA X. 1999. - Turtles from the Upper Cretaceous of Lano (Iberian Peninsula). Estudios del Museo de Ciencias Naturales de Alava 14: 135 - 211." type="journal article" year="1999">Lapparent de Broin &amp; Murelaga 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="MILNER A. R." box="[422,565,1236,1262]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="1441 - 1467" refId="ref44294" refString="MILNER A. R. 2004. - The turtles of the Purbeck Limestone Group of Dorset, southern England. Palaeontology 47 (6): 1441 - 1467. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 0031 - 0239.2004.00418. x" type="journal article" year="2004">Milner 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G. &amp; STERLI J. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D." box="[581,768,1236,1262]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="1257 - 1287" refId="ref41904" refString="JOYCE W. G., STERLI J. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D. 2014. - The skeletal morphology of the solemydid turtle Naomichelys speciosa from the Early Cretaceous of Texas. Journal of Paleontology 88 (6): 1257 - 1287. https: // doi. org / 10.1666 / 14 - 002" type="journal article" year="2014">
Joyce 
<emphasis box="[647,702,1236,1262]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G." box="[132,258,1268,1294]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="65 - 113" refId="ref41684" refString="JOYCE W. G. 2017. - A Review of the Fossil Record of Basal Mesozoic Turtles. Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History 58: 65 - 113. https: // doi. org / 10.3374 / 014.058.0105" type="journal article" year="2017">Joyce 2017</bibRefCitation>
; Pérez-García 
<emphasis box="[425,480,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2020). Neurals V and VI are elongate and hexagonal. Neurals VII and VIII are probably fused. They are wide and hexagonal anteriorly and posteriorly, and narrower on the midline. There are three suprapygals, which are reminiscent of the condition in FMNH PR273, a nearly complete specimen referred to the North American species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hay" authorityYear="1908" box="[438,656,1459,1485]" class="Reptilia" family="Pleurosternidae" genus="Naomichelys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="speciosa">
<emphasis box="[438,656,1459,1485]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">Naomichelys speciosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the number of suprapygals is known to be rather variable in basal turtles. The morphology of the suprapygals and pygal differs from other known helochelydrids, but detailed comparisons are needed in order to assess the systematic value of these characters. The shell surface sculpturing is less prominent on the neurals and becomes more pronounced on the distal part of the costals and on the peripherals, suprapygals, and pygal.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[131,777,215,2028]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">
Helochelydrids are considered by numerous authors to be terrestrial forms (
<bibRefCitation author="LAPPARENT DE BROIN F. DE &amp; MURELAGA X." box="[353,767,1778,1804]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="135 - 211" refId="ref42274" refString="LAPPARENT DE BROIN F. DE &amp; MURELAGA X. 1999. - Turtles from the Upper Cretaceous of Lano (Iberian Peninsula). Estudios del Museo de Ciencias Naturales de Alava 14: 135 - 211." type="journal article" year="1999">Lapparent de Broin &amp; Murelaga 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D. &amp; MOODY R. T. J. &amp; WALKER C. A." box="[132,316,1810,1836]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="75 - 97" refId="ref41777" refString="JOYCE W. G., CHAPMAN S. D., MOODY R. T. J. &amp; WALKER C. A. 2011. - The skull of the solemydid turtle Helochelydra nopcsai from the Early Cretaceous of the Isle of Wight (UK) and a review of Solemydidae. Special Papers in Palaeontology 86: 75 - 97." type="journal article" year="2011">
Joyce 
<emphasis box="[198,251,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
; Scheyer 
<emphasis box="[424,478,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2015). They are known to have limbs and neck covered with osteoderms (
<bibRefCitation author="BARRETT P. M. &amp; CLARKE J. B. &amp; BRINKMAN D. B. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D. &amp; ENSOM P. C." pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="279 - 295" refId="ref36054" refString="BARRETT P. M., CLARKE J. B., BRINKMAN D. B., CHAPMAN S. D. &amp; ENSOM P. C. 2002. - Morphology, histology and identification of the ' granicones' from the Purbeck Limestone Formation (Lower Cretaceous: Berriasian) of Dorset, southern England. Cretaceous Research 23: 279 - 295. https: // doi. org / 10.1006 / cres. 2002.1002" type="journal article" year="2002">
Barrett 
<emphasis box="[724,775,1841,1867]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2002
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G. &amp; STERLI J. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D." box="[205,391,1873,1900]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="1257 - 1287" refId="ref41904" refString="JOYCE W. G., STERLI J. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D. 2014. - The skeletal morphology of the solemydid turtle Naomichelys speciosa from the Early Cretaceous of Texas. Journal of Paleontology 88 (6): 1257 - 1287. https: // doi. org / 10.1666 / 14 - 002" type="journal article" year="2014">
Joyce 
<emphasis box="[272,326,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
; Scheyer 
<emphasis box="[501,555,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2015). Such osteoderms have also been found at Angeac-Charente. Known cranial material suggests a durophagous diet, although it is still unclear exactly which hard-shelled food elements these turtles fed on (
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D. &amp; MOODY R. T. J. &amp; WALKER C. A." box="[365,551,2001,2028]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="75 - 97" refId="ref41777" refString="JOYCE W. G., CHAPMAN S. D., MOODY R. T. J. &amp; WALKER C. A. 2011. - The skull of the solemydid turtle Helochelydra nopcsai from the Early Cretaceous of the Isle of Wight (UK) and a review of Solemydidae. Special Papers in Palaeontology 86: 75 - 97." type="journal article" year="2011">
Joyce 
<emphasis box="[432,486,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="700">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="JOYCE W. G. &amp; STERLI J. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D." box="[566,624,2001,2027]" pageId="19" pageNumber="700" pagination="1257 - 1287" refId="ref41904" refString="JOYCE W. G., STERLI J. &amp; CHAPMAN S. D. 2014. - The skeletal morphology of the solemydid turtle Naomichelys speciosa from the Early Cretaceous of Texas. Journal of Paleontology 88 (6): 1257 - 1287. https: // doi. org / 10.1666 / 14 - 002" type="journal article" year="2014">2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
